ce:section.ce:para:
The structure combined with surface functional groups of N,S-CDs were examined through Fourier-transform infrared spectroscopy (FT-IR). Fig. 2c depicted analyzed results. The intense and wide absorption band observed at 3200 and 3090 cm−1 was induced by the stretching vibration associated with N–H/O–H bonds [59], denoting the presence of amino and hydroxyl groups on the N,S-CDs, rendering them highly hydrophilic. The peak at 2930 and 2610 cm−1 separately indicated the stretching vibrations of C–H [60] and the S–H group [61–63]. The carboxyl group (-COOH) exists in the form of deprotonated carboxylate (
COO ‐
) [64,65]. The peaks at 1570 and 1400 cm−1 were independently corresponded to the antisymmetric and symmetric stretching vibrations of carboxylate CO [66–69]. The feature peaks found at1310, 1120 and 1020 cm−1 stood for the stretching vibrations for C–N, CS/SO, and C–O [48,70]. Additionally, the stretching vibration of C–S bonds was apparent at 648 cm−1 [48]. Based on the FT-IR analysis discussed above, it confirmed that N,S-CDs were favorably doped with nitrogen and sulfur atoms, and their surface possessed abundant active groups consisted of nitrogen, sulfur and oxygen.
